ations in both value and key positions, but that might just duplicate the value/key. However, there isn't an existing solution for that yet. Also, I might consider how `Json.arr` handles order preservation in arrays and the existing check for indices in those arrays.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Circe's JSON Object**\\n\\nI'm exploring whether Circe's JSON object preserves insertion order and if the public API supports this. It seems like a feature that could allow testing field order with literal and interpolated keys and values. I should check if JsonObject handles duplicate keys and top-level null fields differently, as there might be functionality around existing nested values and how top-level JSON primitives are treated without needing an enclosing array or object. This all feels quite technical!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining JSON top-level primitives**\\n\\nI’m looking into existing behaviors where top-level strings and JSON are interpolated rather than treated as literal top-level primitives. I could add tests for different primitive types like `null`, `false`, and numbers, which should help cover parsing in a `singleContext` for literal primitives. There’s a need for a distinct public feature for top-level literals, and I should ensure that all relevant classes are public. I also need to add style type annotations in functions, which feels like a lot to manage!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_DWrmxVww5LG7S9IakUnjgA7K|fc_0f488e3eaffc447e016a3f998e90c8819786b6ef722aa2c885", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.circe/circe-literal_3/0.14.15/src/test/scala/io_circe/circe_literal_3/Circe_literal_3Test.scala", "edits": [{"oldText": "    assert(stringValue(values(2)) == topLevelText)\n    assert(values(3) == Json.True)\n\n  private final case class Details(id: Int, label: String, active: Boolean)\n", "newText": "    assert(stringValue(values(2)) == topLevelText)\n    assert(values(3) == Json.T